{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504592"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.1,0.64,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41632"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26550"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1444"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41632"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents with a one-week history of ear pain, itching, and discharge. He does not have any complaints of hearing impairment or tinnitus. He went to a pool party with his friends 10 days ago where he says he swam all the time while he was there. He has no relevant medical history and takes no regular medications. He does not smoke and drinks two to three beers on weekends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and vitals are stable. When his ear is manipulated prior to the otoscopic examination, he complains of pain. Otoscopic examination reveals erythematous and oedematous ear canal with normal-looking tympanic membrane. The oropharyngeal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative pathogen of this patient\u2019s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Candida albicans","Haemophilus influenzae","Moraxella catarrhalis","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Streptococcus pneumoniae"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with otalgia, ear discharge, pain on ear manipulation, and recent history of swimming most likely has a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eotitis externa (OE).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOE is an infection and inflammation of the external ear canal. The common causative organisms of OE are \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E. Pseudomonas is a ubiquitous water organism and may cause otitis externa with water exposure (eg, swimming). The other common risk factors for OE are foreign bodies inside ears (eg, hearing aid, headphones) and trauma. Patients typically present with otalgia, itching, and ear discharge. On physical examination, they may complain of pain in the ear during manipulation (in contrast to otitis media, where the patient may keep on tugging their ear due to discomfort). Otoscopic examination reveals erythema and oedema in the ear canal. A little discharge may also be seen. Patients diagnosed with otitis externa should be treated with topical antibiotics and steroid drops.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Emay be a causative agent in patients with otomycosis. Otomycosis may be visualised on otoscopic examination and may reveal white cheesy discharge along with erythema within the ear canal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EMoraxella catarrhalis\u003C/em\u003E, \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Eare associated with otitis media which presents with ear pain, hearing loss, and bulging tympanic membrane on otoscopy. This patient\u0027s otoscopic examination reveals a normal tympanic membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The most common causative organisms of otitis external are Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Staphylococcus aureus."],"references":["Roland P, Stroman D. Microbiology of Acute Otitis Externa. Laryngoscope. 2002;112(7):1166-1177. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12169893/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26550"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26550"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-20T12:41:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-20T12:41:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41632"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u